<para/></section><section><title>Using attributes to reduce complexity</title>

<para>Continuing from the same example as above, let's look at ways to reduce the number of arguments being passed. 
Here we put the functionalilty into the button itself:</para>

<example role="live-example">
   <title>More on attributes</title>
   <programlisting language="lzx">
   <textobject><textdata fileref="programs/scripting-tutorial-$17.lzx"/></textobject> 
   </programlisting>
</example>
<?example role="live-example"><title>More on attributes</title><programlisting role="lzx-embednew"><filename>scripting-tutorial-$17.lzx</filename><parameter/><code>
&lt;canvas width="500" height="200"&gt;
  &lt;window x="100" y="60"
        title="Window 2" name="windowTwo" id="windowTwoId"&gt;
    &lt;!-- Moves the second window specified number of pixels 
         in specified direction --&gt;
    &lt;method name="moveWindow" args="buttonObj"&gt;
      direction = buttonObj.getAttribute("direction");
      distance = parseInt(buttonObj.getAttribute("distance"));
      // decide which direction to go
      if (direction == "left") {
       var increment = -1 * distance;
      } else if (direction == "right") {
        var increment = distance;
      }
      var originalX = this.getAttribute('x');
      var newX = originalX + increment;
      this.setAttribute('x', newX);
    &lt;/method&gt;
    &lt;text&gt;This is the second window.&lt;/text&gt;
  &lt;/window&gt;
  &lt;window x="20" y="20" width="300"
      title="Simple Window"&gt;
    &lt;simplelayout axis="x" spacing="4"/&gt;
    &lt;button onclick="windowTwoId.moveWindow(this)"&gt;Left 2
      &lt;attribute name="direction" value="'left'"/&gt;
      &lt;attribute name="distance" value="'2'"/&gt;
    &lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;button onclick="windowTwoId.moveWindow(this)"&gt;Left 20
      &lt;attribute name="direction" value="'left'"/&gt;
      &lt;attribute name="distance" value="'20'"/&gt;
    &lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;button onclick="windowTwoId.moveWindow(this)"&gt;Right 20
      &lt;attribute name="direction" value="'right'"/&gt;
      &lt;attribute name="distance" value="'20'"/&gt;
    &lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;button onclick="windowTwoId.moveWindow(this)"&gt;Right 2
      &lt;attribute name="direction" value="right" type="string"/&gt;
      &lt;attribute name="distance" value="'2'"/&gt;
    &lt;/button&gt;
  &lt;/window&gt;
&lt;/canvas&gt;
</code></programlisting><programlisting>
&lt;canvas width="500" height="200"&gt;
  &lt;window x="100" y="60"
        title="Window 2" name="windowTwo" id="windowTwoId"&gt;
    &lt;!-- Moves the second window specified number of pixels 
         in specified direction --&gt;
    <emphasis role="em">&lt;method name="moveWindow" args="buttonObj"&gt;
      direction = buttonObj.getAttribute("direction");
      distance = parseInt(buttonObj.getAttribute("distance"));</emphasis>
      // decide which direction to go
      if (direction == "left") {
       var increment = -1 * distance;
      } else if (direction == "right") {
        var increment = distance;
      }
      var originalX = this.getAttribute('x');
      var newX = originalX + increment;
      this.setAttribute('x', newX);
    &lt;/method&gt;
    &lt;text&gt;This is the second window.&lt;/text&gt;
  &lt;/window&gt;
  &lt;window x="20" y="20" width="300"
      title="Simple Window"&gt;
    &lt;simplelayout axis="x" spacing="4"/&gt;
    &lt;button onclick="windowTwoId.moveWindow(<emphasis role="em">this</emphasis>)"&gt;Left 2
      <emphasis role="em">&lt;attribute name="direction" value="'left'"/&gt;
      &lt;attribute name="distance" value="'2'"/&gt;</emphasis>
    &lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;button onclick="windowTwoId.moveWindow(<emphasis role="em">this</emphasis>)"&gt;Left 20
      <emphasis role="em">&lt;attribute name="direction" value="'left'"/&gt;
      &lt;attribute name="distance" value="'20'"/&gt;</emphasis>
    &lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;button onclick="windowTwoId.moveWindow(<emphasis role="em">this</emphasis>)"&gt;Right 20
      <emphasis role="em">&lt;attribute name="direction" value="'right'"/&gt;
      &lt;attribute name="distance" value="'20'"/&gt;</emphasis>
    &lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;button onclick="windowTwoId.moveWindow(<emphasis role="em">this</emphasis>)"&gt;Right 2
      <emphasis role="em">&lt;attribute name="direction" value="right" type="string"/&gt;
      &lt;attribute name="distance" value="'2'"/&gt;</emphasis>
    &lt;/button&gt;
  &lt;/window&gt;
&lt;/canvas&gt;
</programlisting><?lzx-edit programs/scripting-tutorial-$17.lzx></example?>

<para>The buttons have attributes which we have named "distance" and "direction". 
The values of those attributes need to be in <emphasis role="i">double quoted strings</emphasis>, because the value needs to be a JavaScript expression, 
not a string or a number. That's the reason for the <literal>value="''"</literal>.
</para>
<para> Alternatively we could give the <indexterm><primary>attribute</primary></indexterm><sgmltag class="element">&lt;attribute&gt;</sgmltag><remark role="fixme">[unknown tag]</remark>
<!--unknown tag: attribute-->
 tag an 
attribute <literal>type="string"</literal>, as shown in the "right 2" button. In this case
the word "right" does not need to be single-quoted.</para>

<para>This example is actually more lengthy than the previous one, but it demonstrates the power of object oriented programming in LZX. 
If the number of attributes were to grow, and if various buttons had different attributes, the code would still remain very clear.</para>

<para/></section></chapter>
